{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_vrtx_01VKzugQZNHti7k1oebyZfk8","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# Security: Multiarch Tuning Operator\n2\t\n3\t## System Namespace Exclusion as a Security Control\n4\t\n5\tThe `shouldIgnorePod` function in `internal/controller/podplacement/pod_model.go` contains hardcoded exclusions that **cannot be overridden by any ClusterPodPlacementConfig configuration**:\n6\t\n7\t```go\n8\tfunc (pod *Pod) shouldIgnorePod(...) bool {\n9\t    return utils.Namespace() == pod.Namespace ||       // operator's own namespace\n10\t           strings.HasPrefix(pod.Namespace, \"kube-\") || // kube-system, kube-public, kube-node-lease\n11\t           pod.Spec.NodeName != \"\" ||\n12\t           pod.HasControlPlaneNodeSelector() ||\n13\t           pod.IsFromDaemonSet() || ...\n14\t}\n15\t```\n16\t\n17\tThese are security controls, not defaults:\n18\t\n19\t- **Operator namespace exclusion**: Prevents the operator from gating its own pods. If the operator gated itself, a pod placement controller failure would prevent the operator from recovering — a self-deadlock. This exclusion is unconditional.\n20\t- **`kube-*` namespace exclusion**: Kubernetes system namespaces host control plane components (API server clients, scheduler, controller-manager sidecar pods). Gating these pods could destabilize the cluster if the pod placement controller is slow or unavailable.\n21\t\n22\t### The openshift-* and hypershift-* Exception\n23\t\n24\t`openshift-*` and `hypershift-*` namespaces are **not** in the hardcoded exclusion list. Whether they are gated depends entirely on the `namespaceSelector` configured on the `ClusterPodPlacementConfig`. This is a known security-relevant gap (referenced in the codebase as FIND-004 from a security audit).\n25\t\n26\t**Risk**: Without a properly configured `namespaceSelector`, pods in `openshift-monitoring`, `openshift-ingress`, `openshift-etcd`, and similar namespaces will receive the scheduling gate. If the pod placement controller is unavailable, those pods will be stuck and critical cluster services will fail to start.\n27\t\n28\t**Mitigation**: Configure `namespaceSelector` on the CPPC to exclude these namespaces:\n29\t\n30\t```yaml\n31\tspec:\n32\t  namespaceSelector:\n33\t    matchExpressions:\n34\t      - key: multiarch.openshift.io/exclude-pod-placement\n35\t        operator: DoesNotExist\n36\t```\n37\t\n38\tThen label any namespace that must be excluded:\n39\t\n40\t```bash\n41\tkubectl label namespace openshift-monitoring multiarch.openshift.io/exclude-pod-placement=true\n42\t```\n43\t\n44\tThe Operator controller documentation and the validation webhook should guide operators to apply this configuration before enabling the CPPC on a production cluster.\n45\t\n46\t## CPPC Singleton as a Security Boundary\n47\t\n48\t`ClusterPodPlacementConfig` is a cluster-scoped singleton (name must be `\"cluster\"`). Its configuration affects every non-excluded namespace cluster-wide. This makes it a high-impact configuration object:\n49\t\n50\t- **`namespaceSelector`**: An overly permissive selector (or an empty one) gates pods in system namespaces. An overly restrictive selector prevents the operator from providing value.\n51\t- **`fallbackArchitecture`**: If set to `amd64` but a node pool only has `arm64` nodes, all pods using the fallback will fail to schedule.\n52\t- **`logVerbosity: TraceAll`**: Enables verbose logging that may expose image URLs and pull secret metadata in logs. Use only for debugging; revert promptly.\n53\t\n54\tBecause a misconfigured CPPC has cluster-wide blast radius, changes to the CPPC should be validated carefully. The admission webhook (`api/v1beta1/clusterpodplacementconfig_webhook.go`) is the enforcement point.\n55\t\n56\t## Webhook Validation: Where to Enforce Constraints\n57\t\n58\tAdmission-time constraints must be enforced in the **validation webhook**, not in the controller reconciliation loop. The validation webhook path is:\n59\t\n60\t```\n61\tapi/v1beta1/clusterpodplacementconfig_webhook.go\n62\t  ValidateCreate() — called on new CPPC creation\n63\t  ValidateUpdate() — called on CPPC updates\n64\t  ValidateDelete() — called on CPPC deletion\n65\t```\n66\t\n67\tThe controller's reconcile loop is not a safe place for validation enforcement because:\n68\t\n69\t1. The reconciler runs asynchronously after admission. By the time it runs, the invalid object is already persisted.\n70\t2. Reconciler errors produce retries, not user-facing admission rejections.\n71\t3. The reconciler cannot prevent the user from writing the object.\n72\t\n73\tExamples of what belongs in the admission webhook:\n74\t- Ensuring `name == \"cluster\"` (already implemented — singleton enforcement)\n75\t- Validating `fallbackArchitecture` is a known value (also enforced by kubebuilder enum marker, but can add semantic validation)\n76\t- Preventing `namespaceSelector` from being set to `{}` (select-all) without an explicit acknowledgment annotation, if that policy is desired\n77\t\n78\t## RBAC Summary by Execution Mode\n79\t\n80\t### Operator Mode (`--enable-operator`)\n81\t\n82\tManages the operand lifecycle. Requires broad permissions to deploy and update Deployments, ServiceAccounts, ClusterRoles, ClusterRoleBindings, Services, ServiceMonitors, and MutatingWebhookConfigurations.\n83\t\n84\tKey permissions:\n85\t- `apps/deployments`: get, list, watch, create, update, patch, delete\n86\t- `rbac.authorization.k8s.io/clusterroles`, `clusterrolebindings`: get, list, watch, create, update, patch, delete\n87\t- `admissionregistration.k8s.io/mutatingwebhookconfigurations`: get, list, watch, create, update, patch, delete\n88\t- `multiarch.openshift.io/clusterpodplacementconfigs`: get, list, watch, update, patch (status)\n89\t- `monitoring.coreos.com/servicemonitors`: get, list, watch, create, update, patch, delete\n90\t\n91\t### Pod Placement Controller Mode (`--enable-ppc-controllers`)\n92\t\n93\tReconciles pods and manages image inspection. Scoped to Pending pods.\n94\t\n95\tKey permissions:\n96\t- `core/pods`: get, list, watch, update, patch (for gate removal and affinity setting)\n97\t- `core/secrets`: get, list, watch (for image pull secrets)\n98\t- `core/configmaps`: get, list, watch (for registry certificates)\n99\t- `core/events`: create, patch (for audit events)\n100\t- `multiarch.openshift.io/clusterpodplacementconfigs`: get, list, watch\n101\t\n102\tThe pod cache is filtered to `status.phase=Pending` via a field selector, reducing the memory footprint and preventing the controller from touching already-scheduled pods.\n103\t\n104\t### Pod Placement Webhook Mode (`--enable-ppc-webhook`)\n105\t\n106\tEvaluates admission requests. Read-only access to cluster state.\n107\t\n108\tKey permissions:\n109\t- `core/namespaces`: get, list, watch (for namespace label evaluation against `namespaceSelector`)\n110\t- `multiarch.openshift.io/clusterpodplacementconfigs`: get, list, watch\n111\t- No write permissions to pods — the webhook mutates the in-flight admission object only, it does not write to the API server directly\n112\t\n113\t### ENoExecEvent Controllers Mode (`--enable-enoexec-event-controllers`)\n114\t\n115\tHandles ENoExecEvent CRs produced by the eBPF daemon.\n116\t\n117\tKey permissions:\n118\t- `multiarch.openshift.io/enoexecevents`: get, list, watch, update, patch, delete\n119\t- `core/nodes`: get, list, watch\n120\t- `core/events`: create, patch\n121\t- Namespace-scoped cache to the operator namespace (`utils.Namespace()`)\n122\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"ee495541-afe4-405f-8ec3-6a1280541269","uuid":"51d097b2-7cdc-41df-9879-d72f1c84dbf2","timestamp":"2026-07-20T18:28:14.399Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/Users/kpais/kpais-workspace/a_b_evals/repos/multiarch-tuning-operator-treatment/agentic/SECURITY.md","content":"# Security: Multiarch Tuning Operator\n\n## System Namespace Exclusion as a Security Control\n\nThe `shouldIgnorePod` function in `internal/controller/podplacement/pod_model.go` contains hardcoded exclusions that **cannot be overridden by any ClusterPodPlacementConfig configuration**:\n\n```go\nfunc (pod *Pod) shouldIgnorePod(...) bool {\n    return utils.Namespace() == pod.Namespace ||       // operator's own namespace\n           strings.HasPrefix(pod.Namespace, \"kube-\") || // kube-system, kube-public, kube-node-lease\n           pod.Spec.NodeName != \"\" ||\n           pod.HasControlPlaneNodeSelector() ||\n           pod.IsFromDaemonSet() || ...\n}\n```\n\nThese are security controls, not defaults:\n\n- **Operator namespace exclusion**: Prevents the operator from gating its own pods. If the operator gated itself, a pod placement controller failure would prevent the operator from recovering — a self-deadlock. This exclusion is unconditional.\n- **`kube-*` namespace exclusion**: Kubernetes system namespaces host control plane components (API server clients, scheduler, controller-manager sidecar pods). Gating these pods could destabilize the cluster if the pod placement controller is slow or unavailable.\n\n### The openshift-* and hypershift-* Exception\n\n`openshift-*` and `hypershift-*` namespaces are **not** in the hardcoded exclusion list. Whether they are gated depends entirely on the `namespaceSelector` configured on the `ClusterPodPlacementConfig`. This is a known security-relevant gap (referenced in the codebase as FIND-004 from a security audit).\n\n**Risk**: Without a properly configured `namespaceSelector`, pods in `openshift-monitoring`, `openshift-ingress`, `openshift-etcd`, and similar namespaces will receive the scheduling gate. If the pod placement controller is unavailable, those pods will be stuck and critical cluster services will fail to start.\n\n**Mitigation**: Configure `namespaceSelector` on the CPPC to exclude these namespaces:\n\n```yaml\nspec:\n  namespaceSelector:\n    matchExpressions:\n      - key: multiarch.openshift.io/exclude-pod-placement\n        operator: DoesNotExist\n```\n\nThen label any namespace that must be excluded:\n\n```bash\nkubectl label namespace openshift-monitoring multiarch.openshift.io/exclude-pod-placement=true\n```\n\nThe Operator controller documentation and the validation webhook should guide operators to apply this configuration before enabling the CPPC on a production cluster.\n\n## CPPC Singleton as a Security Boundary\n\n`ClusterPodPlacementConfig` is a cluster-scoped singleton (name must be `\"cluster\"`). Its configuration affects every non-excluded namespace cluster-wide. This makes it a high-impact configuration object:\n\n- **`namespaceSelector`**: An overly permissive selector (or an empty one) gates pods in system namespaces. An overly restrictive selector prevents the operator from providing value.\n- **`fallbackArchitecture`**: If set to `amd64` but a node pool only has `arm64` nodes, all pods using the fallback will fail to schedule.\n- **`logVerbosity: TraceAll`**: Enables verbose logging that may expose image URLs and pull secret metadata in logs. Use only for debugging; revert promptly.\n\nBecause a misconfigured CPPC has cluster-wide blast radius, changes to the CPPC should be validated carefully. The admission webhook (`api/v1beta1/clusterpodplacementconfig_webhook.go`) is the enforcement point.\n\n## Webhook Validation: Where to Enforce Constraints\n\nAdmission-time constraints must be enforced in the **validation webhook**, not in the controller reconciliation loop. The validation webhook path is:\n\n```\napi/v1beta1/clusterpodplacementconfig_webhook.go\n  ValidateCreate() — called on new CPPC creation\n  ValidateUpdate() — called on CPPC updates\n  ValidateDelete() — called on CPPC deletion\n```\n\nThe controller's reconcile loop is not a safe place for validation enforcement because:\n\n1. The reconciler runs asynchronously after admission. By the time it runs, the invalid object is already persisted.\n2. Reconciler errors produce retries, not user-facing admission rejections.\n3. The reconciler cannot prevent the user from writing the object.\n\nExamples of what belongs in the admission webhook:\n- Ensuring `name == \"cluster\"` (already implemented — singleton enforcement)\n- Validating `fallbackArchitecture` is a known value (also enforced by kubebuilder enum marker, but can add semantic validation)\n- Preventing `namespaceSelector` from being set to `{}` (select-all) without an explicit acknowledgment annotation, if that policy is desired\n\n## RBAC Summary by Execution Mode\n\n### Operator Mode (`--enable-operator`)\n\nManages the operand lifecycle. Requires broad permissions to deploy and update Deployments, ServiceAccounts, ClusterRoles, ClusterRoleBindings, Services, ServiceMonitors, and MutatingWebhookConfigurations.\n\nKey permissions:\n- `apps/deployments`: get, list, watch, create, update, patch, delete\n- `rbac.authorization.k8s.io/clusterroles`, `clusterrolebindings`: get, list, watch, create, update, patch, delete\n- `admissionregistration.k8s.io/mutatingwebhookconfigurations`: get, list, watch, create, update, patch, delete\n- `multiarch.openshift.io/clusterpodplacementconfigs`: get, list, watch, update, patch (status)\n- `monitoring.coreos.com/servicemonitors`: get, list, watch, create, update, patch, delete\n\n### Pod Placement Controller Mode (`--enable-ppc-controllers`)\n\nReconciles pods and manages image inspection. Scoped to Pending pods.\n\nKey permissions:\n- `core/pods`: get, list, watch, update, patch (for gate removal and affinity setting)\n- `core/secrets`: get, list, watch (for image pull secrets)\n- `core/configmaps`: get, list, watch (for registry certificates)\n- `core/events`: create, patch (for audit events)\n- `multiarch.openshift.io/clusterpodplacementconfigs`: get, list, watch\n\nThe pod cache is filtered to `status.phase=Pending` via a field selector, reducing the memory footprint and preventing the controller from touching already-scheduled pods.\n\n### Pod Placement Webhook Mode (`--enable-ppc-webhook`)\n\nEvaluates admission requests. Read-only access to cluster state.\n\nKey permissions:\n- `core/namespaces`: get, list, watch (for namespace label evaluation against `namespaceSelector`)\n- `multiarch.openshift.io/clusterpodplacementconfigs`: get, list, watch\n- No write permissions to pods — the webhook mutates the in-flight admission object only, it does not write to the API server directly\n\n### ENoExecEvent Controllers Mode (`--enable-enoexec-event-controllers`)\n\nHandles ENoExecEvent CRs produced by the eBPF daemon.\n\nKey permissions:\n- `multiarch.openshift.io/enoexecevents`: get, list, watch, update, patch, delete\n- `core/nodes`: get, list, watch\n- `core/events`: create, patch\n- Namespace-scoped cache to the operator namespace (`utils.Namespace()`)\n","numLines":122,"startLine":1,"totalLines":122}}}
